statement.p:
Decide whether each subset of  \R^3 is linearly dependent or linearly independent. 



						\left\{\vec{1  -3 5}, \vec{2  2  4}, \vec{4  -4  14} \right\}



						\left\{\vec{1  7  7}, \vec{2  7  7}, \vec{3  7  7} \right\}



						\left\{\vec{0  0  -1}, \vec{1  0  4} \right\}



						\left\{\vec{9  9  0}, \vec{2  0  1}, \vec{3  5  -4}, \vec{12  12  -1} \right\}

answer.p:
For each of these, when the subset is independent you must prove it, and when the subset is dependent you must give an example of a dependence.


It is dependent. Considering
						c_1\vec{1  -3  5} +c_2\vec{2  2  4} + c_3\vec{4  -4  14} =\vec{0  0 0}
						gives this linear system.

							\syseq{
							 c_1  +  2c_2  +  4c_3  =  0;
              						-3c_1 +  2c_2  -  4c_3  =  0;
              						5c_1 +  4c_2  +  14c_3 =  0  
							}

						Row reduction gives


							\amat{
							 1  2  4  0 ; 
              						-3 2  -4 0 ; 
              						5  4  14 0
							}
							\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
							&\amat{
							 1  2  4  0 ; 
              						0  8  8  0 ; 
              						0  0  0  0
							}


						yields a free variable, so there are infinitely many solutions. For an example of a particular dependence we can set c_3 to be, say, 1.  Then we get  c_2=-1 and c_1=-2.


It is dependent. The linear system that arises here


							\amat{
							1  2  3  0 ; 
              						7  7  7  0 ; 
              						7  7  7  0
							}
							\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
							&\amat{
							1  2  3   0;  
              						0  -7 -14 0 ; 
              						0  0  0   0
							}


						has infinitely many solutions. We can get a particular solution by taking c_3 to be, say, 1, and back-substituting to get the resulting c_2 and c_1.


It is linearly independent. The system


							\amat{
							  0  1  0; 
              						 0  0  0 ; 
              						-1 4  0
							}
							\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
							&\amat{
							-1 4  0 ; 
              						0  1  0 ; 
              						0  0  0 
							}


						has only the solution c_1=0 and c_2=0. (We could also have gotten the answer by inspection - the second vector is obviously not a multiple of the first, and vice versa.)


It is linearly dependent. The linear system

						\amat{
						9  2  3  12  0 ; 
              					9  0  5  12  0 ; 
              					0  1  -4 -1  0
						}

						has more unknowns than equations, and so row reduction must end with at least one variable free (there can't be a contradictory equation because the system is homogeneous, and so has at least the solution of all zeroes).
          						To exhibit a combination, we can reduce to 

          						\amat{
          						 9  2  3  12  0 ; 
              					0  -2 2  0   0 ; 
              					0  0  -3 -1  0
          						}

          						and take, say,  c_4=1. Then we have that  c_3=-\frac{1}{3},c_2=-\frac{1}{3}, and c_1=-\frac{31}{27}.
